Builds an in-memory snapshot of the UI (the virtual DOM).
Diffs it against the previous snapshot.
Applies only the minimal DOM changes needed.



&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
  &lt;meta charset="UTF-8" /&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;Click counter&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;style&gt;
    button { font-size: 1rem; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; }
    p      { font-family: sans-serif; }
  &lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;You clicked &lt;span id="count"&gt;0&lt;/span&gt; times.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;button id="btn"&gt;Click me&lt;/button&gt;

  &lt;script&gt;
    // grab elements
    const btn   = document.getElementById('btn');
    const count = document.getElementById('count');
    let clicks  = 0;

    // attach event listener
    btn.addEventListener('click', () =&gt; {
      clicks += 1;          // update state
      count.textContent = clicks; // update DOM manually
    });
  &lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;


You manipulate the DOM directly (getElementById, .textContent).
State (clicks) lives outside the DOM and must stay in sync by hand.

